title: For Sale:  ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°)Remington No. 1 Argentino Rolling Block Rifle (sale pending)
postcontent:
(Sold pending funds)
REMINGTON SINGLE SHOT MILITARY NUMBER 1 ROLLING BLOCK RIFLE USED AS THE CHIEF SERVICE ARM OF MANY ARMIES IN THE SECOND HALF OF THE 19TH CENTURY. This is a .43 SPANISH (11.15X58MMR) caliber. ANTIQUE – NO FFL TRANSFER REQUIRED.



Probably over one million Remington Number 1 size rolling block rifles were made between 1867 and 1888. They were purchased in large quantities and in many different calibers and configurations by many countries including Argentina, Norway, Denmark, Spain, Turkey, Egypt and Mexico. Barrel lengths and other specifications differed from country to country. They were hard used for long periods of time and fought in many different wars. It was used by either the Spanish or Argentine military. The barrel and receiver both have a few areas of pitting in the metal. The barrel is 35 inches long and has an excellent bore with great rifling and no pitting. There are the usual slight dings and dents but no heavy gouging. The gun has it's cleaning rod. The rifle still functions perfectly. The multi line Remington roll stamp of name and patent dates is on the top tang and is still readable. Not the prettiest rifle I’ve ever sold, but it’s got tons of character and is a great example of 19th Century military history. Antique – No FFL or C&R required – can be shipped right to your door. Like I said before this is not a wall hanger. It has a bright and shiny bore with pronounced rifling. I am including a box of 20 rounds of Ammo, also. Yes Buffalo arms black powder 370 grn, ammo. Perfect for those montana buffalo poaching trips on Ted's private prarie, lol. Keep your brass and you can be reloading with a $50.00 set of dies. Much funner than percussion, lol.

Sorry, I don't have the original box and papers, ha hah. Gun is in good fireable shape. It has been in the safe for many years only to be pulled and cleaned and inspected. Look at my other ads also. I will be selling the bulk of my collection over the next month or so to fund a large project. I will have some things for sale that will interest all different collectors and shooters.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colorado Pro-gun Rally at Capitol Friday, February 8th
postcontent:
Join LIKE-MINDED Americans at a Pro-Second Amendment Rally, on the West Step of the Colorado Capitol. Express your support for your Second Amendment rights, by exercising your First Amendment rights, Friday, February 8th, from noon to 4pm. **Charles Heller** from Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership will be the keynote speaker. Project Appleseed will be offering 'junior shooting sports enthusiasts' presentations on gun safety and the history of rifles, so bring the kids. A day at the Capitol for the kids features an educational tour of the Capitol, including a tour of the legislative areas. Adult activists will be visiting with anti-gun legislators while in the building. Join the fun; make a difference by showing up and being counted. Speakers and activities are added to the event daily. The West Steps is located between 14th and Colfax, on the east side of Lincoln Street.

Pro-gun activists across Colorado have joined together to join the national pro-gun rally on Friday, February 8th.
Guest speakers include:
Charles Heller of Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership
Project Appleseed
Representative Perry Buck
David K. Williams - Gadsden Society
Matthew Hess - Candidate for Colorado Governor

Join us between Noon and 4pm for many activities including:
- Project Appleseed
-Sign Contests
-Tours of the Capitol building
-Junior Shooting Sports Enthusiasts
-Excursions into the building to find senators and representatives
-Presentations on testifying before the legislature
-Group card to Hickenlooper
-Speakers
-Sign Making for Juniors Enthusiasts
-Activist Recruiting – Find your niche and make a difference
-Shooting Sports Village –Trainers, Retailers, Activist Groups
-Give Senator Jesse Ulibarri a ballpoint pen!
-Patriotic song writing for kids

Bring the kids, bring your spouse, bring your grandma! Show your elected representatives that you are paying attention.

Senator Morgan Carroll, Representatives Rhonda Fields and Claire Levy are actively promoting ANTI-FIREARM legislation that will put further restrictions on our liberties!

In response to the growing rhetoric both in our country and in the state of Colorado for expanding gun control laws, local Second Amendment activists will be rallying at the West Steps of the Capitol Denver on February 8th, 2013, at 12 p.m.

While tragedies like what occurred in Newtown Connecticut and Aurora Colorado are horrific and deeply disturbing, we cannot allow the actions of criminals to destroy our heritage and our rights. These rights are continually being fought for and died for as external threats have presented themselves. We champion the soldiers who risk everything to preserve our freedom and liberty when they fight abroad, yet now we are faced with the prospect that we may voluntarily dismantle those same liberties at home because we are filled with fear and sorrow.

This rally on February 8th is being coordinated in solidarity with other pro freedom and pro Second Amendment groups who will be marching on their respective capitols across the country. This rally also follows two previous rallies on our capitol steps that took place on January 9th and January 19th, which received national media attention. We are planning to have a larger turnout than the previous two rallies, and we will look to maintain the momentum we are building to show our lawmakers what the people of Colorado demand from them.

The rally is being organized by Guns for Everyone and many other grassroots activist, to demonstrate to our state legislature as well as the federal government where Colorado stands in the current debate on gun rights. We intend to show that we stand firmly in our Constitutional right to keep and bear arms and that we will not tolerate reactionary political agendas to erode the rights that we have enjoyed in this country for centuries.

As was recently stated to a Westword reporter by one of the rally organizers Edgar Antillon, "Anything against the Second Amendment is not common sense. Anything against the Constitution isn't common sense." Antillon organized the first rally on January 9th and has been a central figure in galvanizing the support of local gun owners in this movement to resist the changes being discussed for Colorado gun laws.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Restored and Write Ready Vintage Fountain Pens
location: Linn Creek. Lake Ozark/Camdenton area., Missouri, United States
postcontent:
I have made my living restoring and selling vintage fountain pens for 17 years. I generally have a a handful of pens on hand at any one time. It can vary from week to week on what I have on hand.  I'm just getting back into guns after a long absence. For me, looks are second to functionality. (I've always ben a believer that 'ugly pens need love too' I don't see why that can't apply to weapons as well...lol)

So in short, I'd like to fill out the stable with a few of the basics. A .45/.44 handgun. Single or double action is fine. A 30/30 & a Mosin Nagant. I already have a Marlin model 15 for small game that I LOVE & a sweet Mossberg 500 w/ the 28" ported barrel & thru-glo sites that has called me out to shoot daily for the past month...lol. 

All of the pens I restore sell/trade come with an unconditional 1 year guarantee. If it gives you any problems, send it back & I'll repair it gratis. (Keep in mind, that if you drop it on the nib & bend it, I'll have to charge you for straightening/retipping/adjustment or ??? depending on the level of damage)

Currently available: Email me direct for detailed pics. REDACTED

Made in the 2nd Quarter of 1949. Red Stripe Parker Dou-Vac Senior. Blue diamond blade style clip. Chevron cap band. 14K fine vac arrow nib. Feed is marked T. Good imprint, weaker on the right side but still visible. The filler unit was broken when it came in, I couldn't find a correct 'clear' filler rod, so the amber that's in it is an acceptable stand in until one can be found. No brassing. Crystal clear barrel lamination's. Overall in 8.75/10 condition. $150.

19-teens-early '20's gold filled Conklin. Medium, medium flexibility 14K #3 Conklin Toledo nib. Flexes to a broad+ line. Engraved with the Chevron pattern. The pen would be 10/10 save one gouge on the back side of the cap. I'll let you judge it's impact. No brassing, dents or significant marks other than the one I just mentioned. Unengraved cap indica. 4 7/8" capped, 3/8" od cap. Spectacular pen. $200

1900-1910's, smooth BHR (black hard rubber) is slightly discolored but un damaged, no chips cracks etc etc. The imprint MONARCH is the only bit of information on the pen. The nib is a superflex fine/medium line with no pressure and flexes to 3B + There is a shield with 14K imprinted on the nib. The same nib imprint used by the Eagle Pencil Co. I suspect this may have been one of their very early offerings. Something else of note is the ribbed grip section, another feature found on pens of the early 1900-1910ish vintage. 5 1/4" capped, 6 11/16" posted, 7/16" at the cap lip. The pen is in wonderful condition and is quite frankly, the best flex nib I have laid hands on in a long time. $125

1914 BCHR CRAIG COIN FILLER made by Sheaffer. 5 3/8" capped, 1/2" od cap. This pen has 2 issues, the first being the VERY flexible Warranted 14K No3 nib (narrow keel style feed). It has a small crack on the right side of the breather hole. The second is the cap. It ha a repaired crack. It has been epoxied closed and then a gold filled cap lip from a 1960's Sheaffer Imperial was added. It fits well and is keeping the crack from ever blowing the cap apart. The pen is unrestored. The nib shouldn't really be used until it's repaired. I can't speak for him, but Greg Minuskin (I'll forward his contact info if needed) repaired one for me like this to near perfect condition. So I'm guessing he can handle it. Very mild overall oxidation, deep crisp chasing. Perfect CRAIG imprint. This is a fairly uncommon pen. It has issues so I'll only ask $125 shipped world wide.

If you are looking for a specific pen or part, contact me. I may be able to help track it down.

postcontent: Kay upright double bass from the first year of manufacture, 1937. The bass is an M-1 Maestro, the top of the line for them in that year. It is original in all its parts except for the replaced bridge. It has violin corners and nicely flamed maple veneer faces for the back and ribs. The neck is two pieces of flamed maple with a 1/4” strip of rosewood between them. The volutes are not separate pieces of wood but carved from the same maple, a rarity. The neck has expert repairs to cracks at both the butt and scroll end, over 20 years old and still solid. The fingerboard and tail piece are made of rosewood. The rare black finished engraved brass plate style gears were made by Kluson. The instrument has the original brown 'reverse sunburst' lacquer finish.
